snippet.textDisplay:
So something I'm confused about with the Djokovic decision. He was granted a visa on November 18. On December 16 he had a Rapid test and a PCR. The Rapid test came back positive, but he thought it was a mistake, and got the PCR test back on the 17th December.
He claims that he was able to get a medical exemption because he'd recently had covid, giving him a temporary immunity. If he only had Covid on the 17th December, how did he expect to get through the exemption/vaccination? It also leaves me wondering why Greg Hunt wrote to Tennis Australia on 29th Nov saying that recent Covid was not a reason for exemption according to the Dept of Health. It's like Djokovic knew he was going to catch covid before coming to Australia.... Novak will be remembered as an antivaxxer who spread the disease in an irresponsible fashion and could not fill in entry forms correctly. He either lied to or misled Australian Border Force by claiming he had not travelled in the 14 days before coming to Australia, then blamed the error on his manager. Then it emerged that he had met with children at a Tennis Belgrade function when he knew he was potentially infectious, before doing a L'Equipe interview after testing positive and not telling the journalist involved. Tennis Australia has to be apportioned some of the blame for telling players that if they were granted a medical exemption for the tournament they could enter unvaccinated, despite the federal government saying otherwise. But many players, including Rafael Nadal and Stefanos Tsitsipas, have pointed out they knew they had to be vaccinated to enter Australia, which again moves the blame back to Djokovic. Let’s face it – Djokovic is a lying steaming pile.
